{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fac74e57-1cfc-48be-8df2-c7f4b3eddbb3","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org:\n\n**Required `.csproj` properties:**\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users invoke (e.g., `dotnet tool run my-mcp-server`)\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — required for stdio transport\n\n**Publish steps:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install with:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\n```\n\nThen they can reference it in their MCP client config pointing to the `my-mcp-server` command. No additional configuration is needed for stdio transport — it works naturally with dotnet tools.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e4c895e2-ce96-4e78-881f-96c979176689","outputTokens":437,"requestId":"2C0C:2FF63B:2AAC154:2F0B359:69FD36CC"},"id":"59f17620-c121-4f05-bd0b-b918b5707149","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:05:25.915Z","parentId":"cb379d10-97e0-4859-bd64-81fec766f443"}
